data.content:
Here's your test rewritten with MSTest's purpose-built collection assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**What changed and why:**

| Before | After | Benefit |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "collection was empty" instead of "expected true" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure says "expected 3 items, found N" |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(...)` | Clearer intent; better failure message |

The `users.All(u => u.IsActive)` check is fine as `Assert.IsTrue` — there's no built-in "assert all match predicate" API, so this is the right tool there.

The key principle: **use the most specific assertion available**. Generic `Assert.IsTrue` produces useless "Expected: True, Actual: False" messages, while specialized assertions tell you *what* went wrong.
